    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-09-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-09-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="340"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d340">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">737.00/9–153</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by <persName corresp="#p_OJL1"
                            >John L. Topping</persName> of the Office of Middle American
                        Affairs</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1953-09-01">September 1,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Political Situation in Cuba</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <item>Participants: The Under Secretary</item>
                    <item>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_FCA1">Aurelio F. Concheso</persName>, Ambassador
                        of Cuba</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>John L. Topping</persName>, <gloss target="#t_MID1"
                            >MID</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_FCA1">Concheso</persName> stated that the
                    attempted revolution at Santiago de Cuba on July 26, 1953<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d340fn1">Documents pertaining to the abortive uprising are in file
                        737.00 for 1953.</note> had strengthened the Government’s position since it
                    had shown that the armed forces are solidly behind the Government, which would
                    handle promptly and efficiently any attempted revolution. He said that a portion
                    of the opposition to the present Government was prepared to participate in
                    elections, but that another portion, headed by deposed <persName
                        corresp="#p_PSC1">Carlos Prío</persName> and his adherents, had thus far
                    preferred to undertake insurrectionary activities. He added that the attempt at
                    Santiago de Cuba had not been directly connected with the <persName
                        corresp="#p_PSC1">Prío</persName> group, but that <persName
                        corresp="#p_PSC1">Prío</persName> had supplied money for the arms used in
                    that effort.</p>
                <p>In response to an inquiry from General <persName corresp="#p_SWB1"
                        >Smith</persName> whether the Cuban Government now felt sufficiently secure
                    to undertake a return to constitutional government, the Ambassador stated that
                    constitutional guarantees would be restored in about four weeks and that the
                    Government would proceed with its plans to hold elections for Congress in June
                    1954.</p>
            </div>
